PARAGRAPH.#text: By Matt Andrejczak SAN FRANCISCO (Dow Jones) -- Sealed Air Corp., maker of Bubble wrap and other plastic packaging for the food industry, said Monday its fourth-quarter net income dropped 41% from a year ago and forecast a weak outlook for this year. Sealed Air, hurt by higher resin and freight costs, has been reducing spending, closing facilities and cutting jobs over the past year. Despite its business slowdown, the company topped Wall Street's profit expectations in the quarter, helping send its stock up 8%.

Headlines.Author: Greg Ip

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Investors muscled back into stocks, but not the stocks that they
fled earlier in the week.The Dow Jones Industrial Average recouped a third of Tuesday's steep
loss, rising 124.72 points, or 1.13%, to 11122.65. But the pullback in
technology stocks continued, albeit at a more modest pace. The Nasdaq
Composite Index, which plummeted a record 229.46 points Tuesday, went on
another wild ride but ultimately fell just 24.15 points Wednesday to
3877.54. The index was even in positive territory for a time, after steep
selling had driven it down as many as 167 points intraday.Although at first glance, it looks as if this week's stock-market
declines -- the industrials dropped nearly 500 points on Monday and Tuesday
-- were a buying opportunity, there is a twist. Money appears to be
rotating out of the stocks that led the market all last year, primarily
technology and Internet-related issues, and into some long-beaten-down
"value" stocks. The Dow Jones Utility Average, for example, jumped
3.8%.The switch may reflect a view that the economic strength that has pushed
up market interest rates in the form of bond yields may be good for
economically sensitive stocks, although bad for high-growth stocks that are
especially sensitive to how interest rates affect the value of earnings far
in the future. Treasury yields rose again to 6.616% in another weak day for
the bond market."What is happening makes sense: In a rising rate environment, companies
that would benefit in a more inflationary environment, like
[economy-sensitive] cyclicals and basic materials, are doing a little
better," said Scott Schermerhorn, head of the value investment team at fund
manager Colonial Management Associates. "People made a lot of money in tech
stocks, they want to lock in profits but still want some market exposure.
They look at utility stocks and say, here's a way to make my portfolio a
little more conservative."For example, on a day that "new economy" darling FreeMarkets
, a Pittsburgh online
auction firm, lost $33.5625 to $244.9375, its cross-town "old-economy"
neighbor, aluminum giant Alcoa
, added $4.6875 to $86. Since
Monday's record high, FreeMarkets' market value has fallen 34% to $8.3
billion. Since its intraday low on Monday, Alcoa's market value has risen
7% to $31.5 billion. That still may not seem a reasonable relationship to
traditional investors, given that FreeMarkets' trailing 12-month revenue
through the third quarter was only $16 million while Alcoa's was $16.4
billion.It has been hard to figure out what the fundamental forces behind this
week's volatile action have been."This is weird stuff going on," said Jon Olesky, head of listed stock
trading at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. "What is awfully amusing to listen
to is people dragging out their soapboxes about fundamentals and
price/earnings ratios. But I think what's at work is very technical."He said tax considerations kept holders of well-performing stocks from
selling until the new year, while Y2K concerns have probably postponed the
seasonal inflow of employee bonuses and other new investment cash by about
a week. Volume on the New York Stock Exchange this week has been at about
one billion shares a day, but Mr. Olesky predicted that next week, "You
will see volumes in the 1.5 billion-share category."There has been little sign of investor panic this week. Quite the
opposite. Benefits consultant Hewitt Associates, which tracks investment
activity in the 401(k) plans of 4.5 million employees, found on both Monday
and Tuesday that investors on balance shifted money into stocks from bonds.
Indeed, individuals have almost unfailingly "bought the dips" throughout
the bull market. Of the 10 largest one-day point drops in the Dow Jones
Industrial Average (nine of which have occurred in the past three years),
eight, including Tuesday's, were followed by strong rebounds.The usual faith of small investors was evident Wednesday.World-wide, stocks fell. Excluding U.S. stocks, the Dow Jones World
Stock Index was down 5.48 points, or 2.88%, to 184.75.In major market action:Stocks were
mostly higher
. On the Big Board, where 1.07 billion shares traded, 1,785 stocks
advanced and 1,320 declined.Bond prices fell
. The 30-year government bond fell 1 1/32, or $10.3125 per $1,000
bond, to yield 6.616%.The dollar was
mixed
. It was quoted at $1.0317 to the euro and 104.30 yen to the dollar,
compared with $1.0313 to the euro and 103.29 yen late Monday in New
York.Write to

gregory.ip@wsj.com
 and Robert McGough at
bob.mcgough@wsj.com

    NEW YORK (CBS.MW) -- Big Wall Street firms and federal
    regulators are discussing a multimillion-dollar settlement of yield-burning abuses in the
    municipal bond market, "people close to the matter" told The Wall Street
    Journal. The government has been probing industry-wide yield-burning for three years.
    Yield-burning occurs when underwriters mark up the prices of bonds sold to municipalities
    to complete complicated deals known as advance refundings. Firms could owe as much as $1
    billion, some lawyers said, although terms of any settlement are likely to be much less.

Headlines.Author: Timothy L. O'Brien
Headlines.Headline: Sealed Air to Buy Grace Unit

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Sealed Air agreed
 to buy the
packaging business of W.R. Grace in a tax-free stock and cash transaction
valued at $4.9 billion. Sealed Air said the purchase will create the
world's largest protective and specialty-packaging firm with more than $2.5
billion in annual sales. Grace said the move marks the end of its
year-and-a-half restructuring program.
